Leetcode 700.Search in Binary Search Tree 

You are given the root of a binary search tree (BST) and an integer val.
Find the node in the BST that the node's value equals val and return the subtree rooted with that node. If such a node does not exist, return null.

A Binary Search Tree (BST) is a special type of binary tree with an ordering property that makes searching efficient.
BST Property
  For every node:
    Left subtree → values less than the node
    Right subtree → values greater than the node

Solution
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    public TreeNode searchBST(TreeNode root, int val) {
        if(root==null)
            return null;
        if(val==root.val)
            return root;
        else if(val<root.val)
            return searchBST(root.left,val);
        else
            return searchBST(root.right,val);
    }
}
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Time & Space ComplexityTime Complexity (TC)
Average case: O(log n)
→ When the BST is balanced, each comparison cuts the tree in half.
Worst case: O(n)
→ When the BST is skewed (like a linked list).

Space Complexity (SC)
Recursive Search
Average: O(log n) (call stack for balanced tree)
Worst: O(n) (skewed tree)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
